<subSubSection type="description">
<paragraph pageNumber="3">Description (characters of holotype, if warranted, given in parentheses). Dorsal fin XII,13 or 14 (14). Anal fin II,15 or 16 (16). Pectoral-fin 13-13 (13-14). Precaudal vertebrae10, caudal vertebrae 22 or 23 (22). Caudal fin elements 8-13-7. Dentary incisor teeth 43-52 (50), lowest counts 43-46 are from smallest specimens, 18.2-21.9 mm; largest specimens, 22.7-30.9 mm, have counts of 49-52. Lateral line extending posteriorly to point between verticals from dorsal-fin spines 10 and 11.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageNumber="3">
All specimens have a preserved color pattern similar to that illustrated in Figure 2a. The main differences are in the intensity with which the dark markings are represented and, in the smaller specimens, the dorsal members of the pairs of spots tend to fuse into a stripe-like marking. The pattern on the anal fin, which is not clear in the Figure 2a, consists of a dusky sub-distal stripe, which is darkest distally, and very similar to that exhibited by 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:BB115E5E-FE8F-4024-8DF5-D90956F26FB0" class="Actinopterygii" family="Blenniidae" genus="Ecsenius" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Ecsenius fijiensis Springer 1988:90" order="Perciformes" pageNumber="3" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="fijiensis">E. fijiensis</taxonomicName>
(Figure 2c).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection type="discussion">
<paragraph pageNumber="3">
Comparisons. 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:BF784097-E1A5-4762-8E08-9522AB4112E2" class="Actinopterygii" family="Blenniidae" genus="Ecsenius" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Ecsenius niue Springer 2002:3" order="Perciformes" pageNumber="3" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="niue">Ecsenius niue</taxonomicName>
will key to couplet 41 in Springer (1988:26), which differentiates 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:B0B50ABE-A8A0-47C8-A7FB-6E107CD1DB70" class="Actinopterygii" family="Blenniidae" genus="Ecsenius" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Ecsenius tigris Springer 1988:98" order="Perciformes" pageNumber="3" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="tigris">E. tigris Springer</taxonomicName>
(islands on the Queensland Plateau) from 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:BB115E5E-FE8F-4024-8DF5-D90956F26FB0" class="Actinopterygii" family="Blenniidae" genus="Ecsenius" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Ecsenius fijiensis Springer 1988:90" order="Perciformes" pageNumber="3" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="fijiensis">E. fijiensis</taxonomicName>
(main Fijian and northern Lau islands) based on color pattern. 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:B0B50ABE-A8A0-47C8-A7FB-6E107CD1DB70" class="Actinopterygii" family="Blenniidae" genus="Ecsenius" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Ecsenius tigris Springer 1988:98" order="Perciformes" pageNumber="3" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="tigris">E. tigris</taxonomicName>
(Figure 2d) was stated to have four to six conspicuous dark spots on the dorsal body contour at the base of the spinous dorsal fin, as opposed to zero to two in 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:BB115E5E-FE8F-4024-8DF5-D90956F26FB0" class="Actinopterygii" family="Blenniidae" genus="Ecsenius" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Ecsenius fijiensis Springer 1988:90" order="Perciformes" pageNumber="3" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="fijiensis">E. fijiensis</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:B0B50ABE-A8A0-47C8-A7FB-6E107CD1DB70" class="Actinopterygii" family="Blenniidae" genus="Ecsenius" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Ecsenius tigris Springer 1988:98" order="Perciformes" pageNumber="3" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="tigris">E. tigris</taxonomicName>
was stated to have two vertical pairs of dark spots on the caudal peduncle, as opposed to three vertical pairs in 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:BB115E5E-FE8F-4024-8DF5-D90956F26FB0" class="Actinopterygii" family="Blenniidae" genus="Ecsenius" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Ecsenius fijiensis Springer 1988:90" order="Perciformes" pageNumber="3" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="fijiensis">E. fijiensis</taxonomicName>
. In 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:BF784097-E1A5-4762-8E08-9522AB4112E2" class="Actinopterygii" family="Blenniidae" genus="Ecsenius" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Ecsenius niue Springer 2002:3" order="Perciformes" pageNumber="3" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="niue">E. niue</taxonomicName>
, there are zero to three very diffuse, dusky spots on the dorsal body contour at the base of the spinous dorsal fin and two vertical pairs of dark spots on the caudal peduncle (the dorsal members of the two pairs may fuse). 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:BF784097-E1A5-4762-8E08-9522AB4112E2" class="Actinopterygii" family="Blenniidae" genus="Ecsenius" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Ecsenius niue Springer 2002:3" order="Perciformes" pageNumber="3" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="niue">Ecsenius niue</taxonomicName>
, thus does not clearly key to one or the other of the two species in the key couplet.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection type="discussion">
<paragraph lastPageNumber="5" pageNumber="4">
The diffuse extension of the posteriormost pair of spots onto the caudal fin of 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:BF784097-E1A5-4762-8E08-9522AB4112E2" class="Actinopterygii" family="Blenniidae" genus="Ecsenius" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Ecsenius niue Springer 2002:3" order="Perciformes" pageNumber="4" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="niue">E. niue</taxonomicName>
is similar to the extensions in 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:B0B50ABE-A8A0-47C8-A7FB-6E107CD1DB70" class="Actinopterygii" family="Blenniidae" genus="Ecsenius" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Ecsenius tigris Springer 1988:98" order="Perciformes" pageNumber="4" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="tigris">E. tigris</taxonomicName>
(Figure2d); however, in 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:B0B50ABE-A8A0-47C8-A7FB-6E107CD1DB70" class="Actinopterygii" family="Blenniidae" genus="Ecsenius" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Ecsenius tigris Springer 1988:98" order="Perciformes" pageNumber="4" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="tigris">E. tigris</taxonomicName>
there are three or four conspicuous dark spots on the body ventral to those on the dorsal body contour below the spinous dorsal fin. These spots are absent in both 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:BF784097-E1A5-4762-8E08-9522AB4112E2" class="Actinopterygii" family="Blenniidae" genus="Ecsenius" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Ecsenius niue Springer 2002:3" order="Perciformes" pageNumber="4" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="niue">E. niue</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:BB115E5E-FE8F-4024-8DF5-D90956F26FB0" class="Actinopterygii" family="Blenniidae" genus="Ecsenius" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Ecsenius fijiensis Springer 1988:90" order="Perciformes" pageNumber="4" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="fijiensis">E. fijiensis</taxonomicName>
. I believe that the color pattern of 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:BF784097-E1A5-4762-8E08-9522AB4112E2" class="Actinopterygii" family="Blenniidae" genus="Ecsenius" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Ecsenius niue Springer 2002:3" order="Perciformes" pageNumber="4" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="niue">E. niue</taxonomicName>
is most similar to that of 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:BB115E5E-FE8F-4024-8DF5-D90956F26FB0" class="Actinopterygii" family="Blenniidae" genus="Ecsenius" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Ecsenius fijiensis Springer 1988:90" order="Perciformes" pageNumber="4" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="fijiensis">E. fijiensis</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection type="distribution">
<paragraph pageNumber="5">Distribution. Known only from Niue Island.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection type="etymology">
<paragraph pageNumber="5">
Etymology. Named 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:BF784097-E1A5-4762-8E08-9522AB4112E2" class="Actinopterygii" family="Blenniidae" genus="Ecsenius" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Ecsenius niue Springer 2002:3" order="Perciformes" pageNumber="5" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="niue">niue</taxonomicName>
in reference to the presumed endemicity of the species to Niue Island. The specific epithet is here used as a noun in apposition - thus, the Niue 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:B3F80107-BABB-495D-BFB7-721DCA10C4F8" class="Actinopterygii" family="Blenniidae" genus="Ecsenius" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Ecsenius McCulloch 1923:121" order="Perciformes" pageNumber="5" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Ecsenius</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
